Design decisions have an emotional dimension — the oscillation,
the false starts, the tension between competing goods. Resolved
decisions look clean. The process of arriving at them is messy.

A future agent reading 'doctor: facts only' sees the conclusion.
Without the story of v1→v2→v3 and the repeated pushback from the
human ('are we being too opinionated?', 'can this be general?',
'is constraints the only namespace?'), the agent doesn't learn HOW
to make decisions in the same spirit. They'll add a prescriptive
check because it seems useful, not understanding that we tried
that and pruned it back three times.

The emotional labor of taste — knowing when to stop adding, when a
feature is actually an opinion, when 'helpful' becomes 'imposing' —
is the hardest thing to transmit. Value notes with stories are the
closest we can get. They won't always work. But without them, the
culture dies with the session.
